John Edward: Language Skills Are Necessary to People of the World · Global Voices
Scotland's independent schools have a history of academic excellence, which continued in 2018, with yet another series of outstanding results in the exams, which were simply further enhanced by individual and collective successes in sports, arts, music and other community efforts.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, which are represented by the Scottish Independent Schools Board (SCIS), struggle to provide the best service level possible to their students and parents.
The aim of independent schools is to prepare their students for the next and highest education levels, the professional careers they will choose and their position as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a school curriculum on demand, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable selection course in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you're talking to someone in a language he understands, then what you say goes into his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, what you say enters his heart."
This is a strong reminder that we cannot simply rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year's exams, we find that languages are at the top of the performance tables, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students studying foreign languages achieved an A degree.
Evidence gathered from 74 SCIS members schools showed that 72 percent of students achieved grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also had grade A.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that will undoubtedly be needed by children and young people in the future.
Languages today, as a selection course, are considered as important as science, technology, engineering and mathematics courses in independent schools and elsewhere.
A UK Employment and Skill Commission survey in 2014 revealed that, as regards the reasons why employers had difficulty filling job vacancies, 17 percent involved lack of language skills.
Therefore, the need to acquire language skills is becoming increasingly urgent so that young people are prepared for their future careers.
Since more future employment opportunities require language knowledge, these skills are necessary in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future, because of this skill you can use throughout your life.
If one is able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, then automatically this multilingual person will have an advantage over competition.
According to YouGov's survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents were unable to speak any foreign language well enough to have a debate, while French was the only language to speak a two-digit percentage of respondents (15 percent).
For this reason, investing in language teaching today is important for today's children.
Knowledge of many languages, especially the languages of developing economies, will give children better opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some schools will focus on the most classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered more important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
For whatever your child is interested, there will always be some languages to choose from in independent schools, which have specialized teaching staff in this area.
Scotland's independent schools loyally provide a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to achieve, whatever the future holds for them.
One cannot deny today that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be extremely important for the future of the country, so this reality should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be regarded as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, multiculturality and excellence for Scottish youth.
They have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Independent Schools Board.
