"However, we see no corresponding response from the US," he said.
"Without confidence in the US there will be no trust in our national security and under such conditions there is no way to unilaterally begin our disarmament."
While Ri repeated well-known North Korea complaints about Washington's resistance to the possibility of a "stepping" approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded as it gradually progressed in the process, his statement was important in that it did not completely block unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to the joint announcement of Kim Yong Eun and Donald Trump at the first summit to take place between an acting US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work on "denuclearisation of the Korean peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea seeks to officially end the 1950–53 Korean war, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first "deliver" its nuclear weapons.
Washington also resisted calls for relaxation of the harsh international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The U.S. insists on becoming 'first denuclearisation' and increasing pressure by threatening sanctions to achieve their cause by blackmailing, putting obstacles even to 'the declaration of end of war'," Ri said.
"The notion that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream of those who do not know us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions deepen our mistrust."
Ri made no mention of a planned second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. chief pointed out to the United Nations earlier this week.
The minister, however, pointed out three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the last five months and added: "If the partner on the issue of denuclearisation were South Korea rather than the US, denuclearizing the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a dead end."
Even so, the tone of Ree's speech was very different from last year, when he told the United Nations General Assembly that targeting the U.S. mainland with North Korean ballistic missiles was inevitable because "Bad President" Trump called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, drew Kim's praise for his courage to move forward with disarmament measures, but said that much still needs to be done and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is denuclearized.
