Harvard students attend classes on how to rest enough
This year, a new course at Harvard University seeks all undergraduate students to sleep more in an effort to combat the growing bunch of culture of overnight study by consuming a lot of caffeine.
An academic discovered that students at number 1 university worldwide often do not know basic things, e.g. how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chisler, a professor of medical sleep at Harvard Medical School and a qualified doctor at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"In the end, a girl came to me and said, "Why am I just learning about this in my last year?".
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - something that surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, first started this year, explains to students the basic principles on how good sleeping habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as to improving general well-being.
Paul Bareira, professor of Psychiatry at Harvard School of Medicine and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to include the course when it was found that students were sleepless within the week to a significant extent.
The hourly course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In a section there is the image of a student dormitory, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sports shoes and books, to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, how sports performance is affected by sleep shortages, as well as the importance of routine sleep.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know it will not change students' behavior directly.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have the right to know the health effects when you choose to smoke," Professor Chisler added.
His culture of boasting because you studied all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students means that sleep deprivation is a problem that swells.
Enough sleep, good quality, should be the "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, even to avoid weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in a state of starvation, resulting in a lasting feeling of hunger.
Raymond Shaw, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemistry and natural biology, helped Professor Chisler design the course, having attended one of his classes last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said his class opened his eyes and inspired him to push for a lesson across the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to attend a similar program before starting their studies at this highly competitive educational institution.
Professor Chisler advised students to set up a warning for the time they should go to bed, as well as an alarm clock for the waking hour, and to know the harmful consequences of "blue light" emitted by electronic monitors and LED lighting, which can disrupt circadian rhythm, leading to sleep problems.
