China announced an increase of 14% in the number of its citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
Over 820,000 people are affected in the country, according to health services.
Only in the second quarter of 2018 were approximately 40,000 new cases reported.
In their overwhelming majority, the new cases were broadcast through sexual contact, marking a change in relation to the past.
Traditionally, HIV virus spread rapidly in some parts of China due to transfusions of contaminated blood.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way was almost zero, as Chinese health officials had stated at a conference in Yunan Province.
However, compared to last year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
The transmission of HIV through sexual contact is a very serious issue for the LGBT community of China.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against the LGBT community remains a common phenomenon.
Due to the country's conservative values, studies estimate that 70-90% of men who have sexual intercourse with men will eventually marry women.
Many cases of transmission of these diseases are due to inadequate sexual protection in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to anti-HIV drugs, as part of the effort to address the problem.
