Europe took first place again, as Danish chief Thomas Bjorn's team reached the 14.5 points needed to defeat the United States.
U.S. team star Phil Mikelston, who fought hard during the longest of the tournament, threw his shot into the water in the par-3 16th hole, granting the victory to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shone in all his rounds and thus became 1 of the 4 players who achieved 5–0 since the current form of the tournament began in 1979.
American Jordan Speed was defeated at 5&4 by the lowest in the European team's player ranking, Danish Thorbjorn Olsen.
The player with the best ranking in the world, Dustin Johnson, scored 2 and 1 against Ian Pulter from England, who may have played his last game in a Ryder Cup.
Spanish veteran of eight Ryder Cups, Sergio Garcia was crowned the most victorious European of all time in the tournament with total points of 25.5.
"I usually don't cry, but today I can't hold on.
It's been a tough year.
I'm grateful to Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I'm so glad we got the cup back.
It's all for the team and I'm glad I could help," Garcia said moved after the European victory.
He gives the baton to his fellow countryman John Ram, who defeated American golf legend Tiger Woods 2&1 in an individual game Sunday.
"I feel incredible pride in defeating Tiger Woods, I grew up admiring this guy," said 23-year-old Ram.
Woods lost in all four of his matches in France and now has a career record at the Ryder Cup 13-21-3.
Unusual statistics for one of the greatest players of all time, who has won 14 major titles and has only been surpassed by Jack Niklaus.
The U.S. team had difficulty all weekend finding a target, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas, and Tony Fino, who played high-level golf throughout the tournament.
American chief Jim Farrick spoke after his team's disappointing performance, "I'm proud of these kids, they fought it.
At times this morning we have pushed Europe quite hard.
We fought hard.
Congratulations to Thomas.
He's a great leader.
All 12 players played very well.
We'll regroup, work with the U.S. PGA and the Ryder Cup Commission and move forward.
I love those 12 kids and I'm proud to be their leader.
We have to admit it.
They were better than us."
Update on the red tide: Concentrations are reduced in the provinces of Pinelas, Manati and Sarasota
The newest announcement from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general fall in Red Tide gatherings for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, conditions of uneven spots are observed in areas of the provinces of Pinelas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which suggests a reduction in concentrations.
A spot of Red Tide extends to about 130 miles of coastline from the northern Pinella province to the southern Li province.
Spots are located about 10 miles off the Hillsborough coast, but at less points than last week.
Red Tide has also been observed in the province of Pasco.
Moderate gatherings were recorded on the coast and off the coast of Pinella Province last week, low to high gatherings were recorded off the coast in Hillsborough Province, background gatherings to high concentrations in Manati Province, background gatherings to high shore concentrations or off coast in Sarasota Province, background gatherings to moderate concentrations in Charlotte Province, background gatherings to high shore concentrations or off coast in Lee Province and low concentrations in Collier Province.
Intrusions in the respiratory system continue to be recorded in the provinces of Pinelas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory disturbances were reported in northwestern Florida in the last week.
